1 Intro

This week we learn how to conduct one-way analysis of variance (ANOVA), including checking assumptions, fitting model, and running post-hoc analyses.

5 ANOVA Model

5.1 Fitting main model

We can use aov() function to fit an ANOVA model. The model syntax is the same as a lm model.

m <- aov(Variable1 ~ AUDITCat, data = d)
summary(m)
##              Df Sum Sq Mean Sq F value Pr(>F)
## AUDITCat      2    144    71.9    1.27   0.28
## Residuals   377  21406    56.8

Alternatively, recall that ANOVA model is also a regression. Therefore, we can also fit our model using the lm() function and use the Anova() function from the car package to obtain relevant ANOVA statistics.

lmm <- lm(Variable1 ~ AUDITCat, data = d)
summary(lmm)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = Variable1 ~ AUDITCat, data = d)
## 
## Residuals:
##     Min      1Q  Median      3Q     Max 
## -24.915  -5.090   0.085   5.085  18.910 
## 
## Coefficients:
##                  Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept)        29.090      0.769   37.83   <2e-16 ***
## AUDITCatAt Risk     0.295      1.383    0.21     0.83    
## AUDITCatModerate   -1.175      0.909   -1.29     0.20    
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 7.54 on 377 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.00668,    Adjusted R-squared:  0.00141 
## F-statistic: 1.27 on 2 and 377 DF,  p-value: 0.283

Our lm model gives output like how we fit a model with categorical predictor using dummy coding. It will give you tests of individual groups against the reference groups, but wont give us a test of the factor as a whole. However, we still can obtain a ANOVA table for this model using the Anova() function.

Anova(lmm)
## Anova Table (Type II tests)
## 
## Response: Variable1
##           Sum Sq  Df F value Pr(>F)
## AUDITCat     144   2    1.27   0.28
## Residuals  21406 377

You can see that the output from the aov model and Anova model are the same. Both tell us whether there is a group difference in the outcome (1 or more group means are statistically significantly different from each other).

There are advantages of using a LM model. With this approach, you could basically fit the same model(s) that you would with a ANOVA model, with the advantage that LM do not require balanced designs but allows both categorical and continuous predictors (e.g., you could include continuous covariates easily) as well as some useful functions for post-hoc analyses. LMs can do everything that t-tests and various ANOVAs can, but with greater flexibility.

5.2 Assumptions for ANOVA

Assumptions for ANOVA are quite similiar to linear regression (because it is technically a regression).

5.2.1 Normality of residuals

To check normality of residuals, we can plot standardised residuals using a QQ plot.

plot(lmm, 2)

5.2.2 Homogeneity of variance

For Homogeneity of variance, we can either use

  • Residual vs predicted plot
plot(lmm, 1)

  • Levenes test
leveneTest(Variable1 ~ AUDITCat, data = d)
## Levene's Test for Homogeneity of Variance (center = median)
##        Df F value Pr(>F)
## group   2    0.12   0.89
##       377

5.2.3 Homogeneity Corrections

If Homogeneity of variance is violated, we will use either Brown-Forsythe or Welch test.

# Brown-Forsythe
bf.test(Variable1 ~ AUDITCat, data = d)
## 
##   Brown-Forsythe Test (alpha = 0.05) 
## ------------------------------------------------------------- 
##   data : Variable1 and AUDITCat 
## 
##   statistic  : 1.36 
##   num df     : 2 
##   denom df   : 181 
##   p.value    : 0.2592 
## 
##   Result     : Difference is not statistically significant. 
## -------------------------------------------------------------
# Welch
welch.test(Variable1 ~ AUDITCat, data = d)
## 
##   Welch's Heteroscedastic F Test (alpha = 0.05) 
## ------------------------------------------------------------- 
##   data : Variable1 and AUDITCat 
## 
##   statistic  : 1.323 
##   num df     : 2 
##   denom df   : 109.8 
##   p.value    : 0.2705 
## 
##   Result     : Difference is not statistically significant. 
## -------------------------------------------------------------

5.2.4 Outliers

We can pretty much use the same methods for regression to check outliers for ANOVA.

5.3 Effect sizes

Eta-squared or omega-squared can be obtained using functions the effectsize package.

Sample Write-up for non-sig ANOVA

A one-way ANOVA was used to examine the difference in Variable 1 across different levels of alcohol consumption. Prior to analysis, assumption of normality was checked using inspection of Q-Q plot of standardized residuals and found supported. Levenes statistic was non-significant (p = 0.36) indicating that the assumption of homogeneity of variance was met. The results were non-significant, showing that Abstainer, Moderate Drinkers, and people who are At Risk of alcohol addiction are not different in their level of Variable1 F(2, 377) = 1.31, p = 0.27.

Notes : If you did not have a significant ANOVA result, you would stop at this point and just report the ANOVA result. For learning purposes, we will go ahead with Post Hoc Tests.

6 Pairwise comparison

ANOVA only tells us whether there is a group difference, but we dont know which group is different from the other. When the result from ANOVA is significant (p < .05), we can use a follow-up test to find where the differences are.

To conduct follow-up test, we can use the emmeans package that works with both aov and lm models.

em <- emmeans(lmm, pairwise ~ AUDITCat)

The default adjustment is TukeyHSD. We can choose another method, such as Bonferroni by adding an adjust = Bonferroni argument.

em_b <- emmeans(lmm, pairwise ~ AUDITCat, adjust = "Bonferroni")

Summarise our results. We add infer= TRUE argument to show p-values.

  • TukeyHSD
summary(em, infer = TRUE)
## $emmeans

6.1 Cohens d

Cohens d is the effect size for the different between two groups. It is simply a measure of the distance between two means, measured in standard deviations. When we have more than two groups, we can use eff_size() to calculate standardized effect sizes are typically calculated using pairwise differences of estimates. This function takes our emmeans model result, along with two arguments, sigma = sigma(model_name) to specify the Standard Deviation of our model, and edf = df.residual(model_name) to specify the equivalent degrees of freedom for the sigma.

eff_size(em, sigma = sigma(lmm), edf = df.residual(lmm))
## Since 'object' is a list, we are using the contrasts already present.
##  contrast               effect.size    SE  df lower.CL upper.CL
##  (Abstainer - At Risk)      -0.0391 0.184 377  -0.3999    0.322
##  (Abstainer - Moderate)      0.1559 0.121 377  -0.0817    0.394
##  (At Risk - Moderate)        0.1950 0.166 377  -0.1308    0.521
## 
## sigma used for effect sizes: 7.535 
## Confidence level used: 0.95

If we only have two groups in our predictor, we can use the cohen_d() function (this wont work for this model because we have three groups).

cohens_d(Variable1 ~ AUDITCat, data = d)
## Error: Grouping variable y must have exactly 2 levels.

7 Visualising results

We can use the visreg package to graph the results from the lm model.

visreg(lmm,
       xvar = "AUDITCat",
       overlay = TRUE, partial = FALSE, band = TRUE, rug = FALSE, gg = TRUE)

Alternatively, we can use the emmip() function to plot our result. This function takes the emmeans model result, rather than the lm model.

emmip(em, ~ AUDITCat, CIs = TRUE) +
  ylab("Variable1") + xlab("Alcohol Consumption")

Sample Write-up for sig ANOVA

A one-way ANOVA was used to examine the difference in Variable 1 across different levels of alcohol consumption. Prior to analysis, assumption of normality was checked using inspection of Q-Q plot of standardized residuals and found supported. Levenes statistic was non-significant (p = 0.36) indicating that the assumption of homogeneity of variance was met. The results were significant, showing that Abstainer, Moderate Drinkers, and people who are At Risk of alcohol addiction are not different in their level of Variable1 F(2, 377) = 1.31, p = 0.27.

Tukeys post hoc analyses (using an of .05) revealed that participants in the Abstainer group (M = 31.47, SD = 4.57) experienced less Variable1 compared to the At Risk group (M = 32.29, SD = 4.32), (b = -0.29 [95% CI -3.55, 2.96], p = .975), with a negative effect d = -0.19. Both Abstainer and At Risk groups showed higher level of Variable1 than Moderate (M = 31.17, SD = 4.08) group, b = 1.17 [95% CI -0.97, 3.31], p = .401, and b = 1.47 [95% CI -1.47, 4.40], p = .467, respectively. These were small differences with d = 0.07 and 0.26, respectively.
